In [[mathematics]], in the field of [[topology]], a [[topological space]] is said to be '''collectionwise Hausdorff''' if given any closed discrete collection of points in the topological space, there are pairwise disjoint open sets containing the points.<ref>FD Tall, [http://www.projecteuclid.org/euclid.pjm/1102867878 The density topology], [[Pacific Journal of Mathematics]], 1976 </ref> A ''closed discrete'' set ''S'' of a topology ''X'' is one where every point of ''X'' has a neighborhood that intersects at most one point from ''S''. Every [[T1 space]] which is collectionwise Hausdorff is also [[Hausdorff space|Hausdorff]].

[[Metrizable space]]s are [[Collectionwise normal|collectionwise normal spaces]] and are hence, in particular, collectionwise Hausdorff.

